00:04:18.850 --> 00:04:19.720
ALAN STEWART: No.

00:04:19.720 --> 00:04:20.740
BRADY HARAN: If you don't
read or write

00:04:20.740 --> 00:04:22.390
music, what do you do?

00:04:22.390 --> 00:04:26.330
Do you just learn what
key sounds like what?

00:04:26.330 --> 00:04:29.150
And when you press these in this
order, it sounds good?

00:04:29.150 --> 00:04:30.600
ALAN STEWART: Yeah.

00:04:30.600 --> 00:04:31.460
I play by ear.

00:04:31.460 --> 00:04:36.830
So if I hear something, as long
as it's not like Bach or

00:04:36.830 --> 00:04:39.610
something, I can usually
emulate it, try

00:04:39.610 --> 00:04:42.200
and copy what I hear.

00:04:42.200 --> 00:04:47.020
And I've been told I have
perfect pitch, which is like

00:04:47.020 --> 00:04:52.470
the ability to hear a note and
just say, oh, that's an A. So

00:04:52.470 --> 00:04:53.440
I guess that helps.

00:04:53.440 --> 00:04:54.070
BRADY HARAN: OK.

00:04:54.070 --> 00:04:54.790
Don't look.

00:04:54.790 --> 00:04:55.440
What's this?

