00:10:37.950 --> 00:10:40.540
very unprofessional way.

00:10:40.540 --> 00:10:40.970
BRADY HARAN: OK.

00:10:40.970 --> 00:10:45.210
ALAN STEWART: I mixed together
trumpets and piccolos and

00:10:45.210 --> 00:10:48.680
various presets on the keyboard
until I had something

00:10:48.680 --> 00:10:52.160
that sounded squeaky and
slightly annoying.

00:10:52.160 --> 00:10:54.270
BRADY HARAN: So it's just a
composite of other instruments

00:10:54.270 --> 00:10:55.740
that sounds squeaky
and annoying.

00:10:55.740 --> 00:10:57.220
ALAN STEWART: Layered on
top of each other.

00:10:57.220 --> 00:10:57.880
BRADY HARAN: Yeah?

00:10:57.880 --> 00:10:58.612
ALAN STEWART: Yeah.

00:10:58.612 --> 00:11:00.450
BRADY HARAN: Can we
load that on?

00:11:00.450 --> 00:11:01.982
Can we have a listen to
what they sound like?

00:11:01.982 --> 00:11:03.060
ALAN STEWART: Here it is.

00:11:03.060 --> 00:11:04.764
[NOTES PLAYING]

00:11:04.764 --> 00:11:06.921
BRADY HARAN: So if you hit
different keys, like--

00:11:06.921 --> 00:11:12.765
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:11:12.765 --> 00:11:14.230
ALAN STEWART: Like that.

00:11:14.230 --> 00:11:14.745
BRADY HARAN: OK.

00:11:14.745 --> 00:11:16.050
So that's how we got
our bagpipes.

00:11:16.050 --> 00:11:18.640
I tell you what, I'm going to
grab the camera, and you can

00:11:18.640 --> 00:11:21.790
talk through the Fibonacciness
of it all.

00:11:21.790 --> 00:11:22.510
ALAN STEWART: OK.

00:11:22.510 --> 00:11:25.160
BRADY HARAN: Alan, you've
made bagpipe noise.

00:11:25.160 --> 00:11:27.450
Talk to me about the
Fibonacciness of

00:11:27.450 --> 00:11:29.045
this piece of music.

00:11:29.045 --> 00:11:30.130
ALAN STEWART: OK.

00:11:30.130 --> 00:11:34.820
The original piece is in B flat,
because that's what I

00:11:34.820 --> 00:11:36.345
thought bagpipes
were tuned to.

00:11:36.345 --> 00:11:39.160
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:11:39.160 --> 00:11:40.980
ALAN STEWART: That's the
scale of B flat.

00:11:40.980 --> 00:11:44.150
But I think to make it simpler
to explain, I'll actually play

00:11:44.150 --> 00:11:46.230
it in C. So you can
number the notes.

00:11:46.230 --> 00:11:51.920
Here's the very first note--
number 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7.

00:11:51.920 --> 00:11:55.870
And then, of course, the eighth
note is the octave.

00:11:55.870 --> 00:11:58.510
What I did was I took
the terms in

00:11:58.510 --> 00:11:59.375
the Fibonacci sequence.

00:11:59.375 --> 00:12:03.690
And I mapped them onto
the musical scale.

00:12:03.690 --> 00:12:09.250
So the Fibonacci sequence
starts 1, 1, 2, 3, 5.

00:12:09.250 --> 00:12:15.054
So that just comes out
as 1, 1, 2, 3, 5.

00:12:15.054 --> 00:12:17.350
The next term is 8.

00:12:17.350 --> 00:12:20.290
So I could jump up to
the eighth note.

00:12:20.290 --> 00:12:24.940
But instead, I decided to take
it full circle and just go

00:12:24.940 --> 00:12:26.810
back to the first note.

00:12:26.810 --> 00:12:28.490
I mean, it's the same note.

00:12:28.490 --> 00:12:29.380
It's still a C.

00:12:29.380 --> 00:12:29.805
[NOTE PLAYING]

00:12:29.805 --> 00:12:31.380
ALAN STEWART: So that's
the eighth note.

00:12:31.380 --> 00:12:37.186
So it goes 1, 1, 2, 3, 5, 8.

00:12:37.186 --> 00:12:40.510
The next term in the Fibonacci
sequence is 13.

00:12:40.510 --> 00:12:44.440
So I suppose I could
have continued to

00:12:44.440 --> 00:12:46.540
climb up the keyboard.

00:12:46.540 --> 00:12:48.140
The 13th note is--

00:12:48.140 --> 00:12:48.510
[NOTE PLAYING]

00:12:48.510 --> 00:12:50.210
ALAN STEWART: --that.

00:12:50.210 --> 00:12:51.410
The next term is 21.

00:12:51.410 --> 00:12:53.020
The 21st note is--

00:12:53.020 --> 00:12:53.450
[NOTE PLAYING]

00:12:53.450 --> 00:12:54.805
ALAN STEWART: --that.

00:12:54.805 --> 00:12:57.535
But that will not sound nice.

00:12:57.535 --> 00:13:02.585
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:13:02.585 --> 00:13:05.160
ALAN STEWART: It doesn't
sound right.

00:13:05.160 --> 00:13:09.310
So can I use maths?

00:13:09.310 --> 00:13:10.710
Thanks.

00:13:10.710 --> 00:13:14.170
What I did was I took
all the terms of

00:13:14.170 --> 00:13:14.975
the Fibonacci sequence.

00:13:14.975 --> 00:13:22.860
And I did mod 7 of the term,
which basically means if you

00:13:22.860 --> 00:13:26.210
take the number-- there's
the Fibonacci number--

00:13:26.210 --> 00:13:32.560
and divide it by 7, what
remainder are you left with?

00:13:32.560 --> 00:13:36.300
So if you take, say, the number
8 and divide that by 7,

00:13:36.300 --> 00:13:40.630
obviously you're going
to get 1 left over.

00:13:40.630 --> 00:13:43.950
If you take 13 and divide that
by 7, you're going to have a

00:13:43.950 --> 00:13:46.740
remainder of 6.

00:13:46.740 --> 00:13:52.730
So in this column here, these
are the result of doing mod 7

00:13:52.730 --> 00:13:55.290
on all the Fibonacci terms.

00:13:55.290 --> 00:13:59.350
And this then allows you to map
the notes into one sort of

00:13:59.350 --> 00:14:01.050
zone on the keyboard.

00:14:01.050 --> 00:14:07.206
Well, it gives you 1, 1,
2, 3, 5, 1, 6, 0, 6,

00:14:07.206 --> 00:14:09.130
6, 5, and so on.

00:14:09.130 --> 00:14:14.720
Then I just took those numbers
and mapped them onto the C

00:14:14.720 --> 00:14:15.530
Major scale.

00:14:15.530 --> 00:14:16.735
BRADY HARAN: What do you get?

00:14:16.735 --> 00:14:17.765
ALAN STEWART: You get this.

00:14:17.765 --> 00:14:27.640
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:14:27.640 --> 00:14:30.520
ALAN STEWART: Which I've clearly
just played in an

00:14:30.520 --> 00:14:32.780
awful way, because every note
had the same length.

00:14:32.780 --> 00:14:35.280
So to give it a bit
more rhythm--

00:14:35.280 --> 00:14:37.770
because the Scots like
their rhythm--

00:14:37.770 --> 00:14:40.750
I just arbitrarily made the
notes whatever length I

00:14:40.750 --> 00:14:42.070
thought sounded best.

00:14:42.070 --> 00:14:43.555
So what you end up with is--

00:14:43.555 --> 00:14:52.090
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:14:52.090 --> 00:14:55.760
ALAN STEWART: Which has a bit
more of a lilt to it.

00:14:55.760 --> 00:14:56.770
It just sounds more musical.

00:14:56.770 --> 00:14:58.550
BRADY HARAN: I'm incredibly
impressed by this, because I

00:14:58.550 --> 00:14:59.836
couldn't do this.

00:14:59.836 --> 00:15:02.980
I'm impressed by anything
I can't do.

00:15:02.980 --> 00:15:03.420
Cool.

00:15:03.420 --> 00:15:04.580
ALAN STEWART: Can I just point
something out about the

00:15:04.580 --> 00:15:06.030
Fibonacci sequence, though?

00:15:06.030 --> 00:15:11.060
Is that there I just
played 16 notes.

00:15:11.060 --> 00:15:14.310
So you may say, OK, well,
what's the 17th note?

00:15:14.310 --> 00:15:18.860
It turns out that the 17th
note is note number 1.

00:15:18.860 --> 00:15:19.340
[NOTE PLAYING]

00:15:19.340 --> 00:15:21.660
ALAN STEWART: The 18th notes
is note number 1.

00:15:21.660 --> 00:15:22.325
[NOTE PLAYING]

00:15:22.325 --> 00:15:25.260
ALAN STEWART: The next note
is note number 2, and

00:15:25.260 --> 00:15:27.060
then 3, and then 5.

00:15:27.060 --> 00:15:29.180
And it turns out that it's
actually exactly the same

00:15:29.180 --> 00:15:31.140
sequence again.

00:15:31.140 --> 00:15:36.970
The same 16 notes just
keep on cycling.

00:15:36.970 --> 00:15:38.960
I know we don't need
to show you this.

00:15:38.960 --> 00:15:45.880
But on the spreadsheet, you can
just keep on going up the

00:15:45.880 --> 00:15:47.130
Fibonacci sequence.

00:15:50.960 --> 00:15:55.490
The remainder, the mod 7 number
just keeps cycling.

00:15:55.490 --> 00:15:58.410
I don't know if I'm explaining
that well.

00:15:58.410 --> 00:16:01.360
So there is no more to
the Fibonacci music.

00:16:01.360 --> 00:16:04.340
I couldn't possibly have done
any more mapping, because it

00:16:04.340 --> 00:16:05.980
just keeps repeating.

00:16:05.980 --> 00:16:07.300
BRADY HARAN: Man,
that's awesome.

00:16:07.300 --> 00:16:08.635
ALAN STEWART: Maybe.

00:16:08.635 --> 00:16:09.995
BRADY HARAN: I'm sure there's
a perfectly logical reason.

00:16:09.995 --> 00:16:11.190
ALAN STEWART: I'm
sure there is.

00:16:11.190 --> 00:16:15.110
And being a physicist, I'm not
quite good enough at the maths

00:16:15.110 --> 00:16:17.540
to be able to explain
why that is.

00:16:17.540 --> 00:16:19.685
Maybe a numberphile will be able
to explain what is it.

00:16:19.685 --> 00:16:20.475
BRADY HARAN: Excellent.

00:16:20.475 --> 00:16:23.830
ALAN STEWART: Anyway.

00:16:23.830 --> 00:16:26.150
That's one Fibonacci element.

00:16:26.150 --> 00:16:32.910
The other thing is the tempo
is 89 beats per minute.

00:16:32.910 --> 00:16:37.360
There's a pulse, click to the
music that just taps a regular

00:16:37.360 --> 00:16:41.250
89 beats in a minute.

00:16:41.250 --> 00:16:46.300
Now the drumming in the song
isn't just a simple pulse of

00:16:46.300 --> 00:16:47.690
89 beats per minute.

00:16:47.690 --> 00:16:49.070
BRADY HARAN: But where's
that pulse?

00:16:49.070 --> 00:16:50.010
I can't hear a pulse.

00:16:50.010 --> 00:16:52.650
ALAN STEWART: I had a click
track in Audacity that was

00:16:52.650 --> 00:16:55.490
just constantly ticking at
89 beats per minutes.

00:16:55.490 --> 00:16:56.410
BRADY HARAN: And then
you took that out?

00:16:56.410 --> 00:16:58.540
ALAN STEWART: I took that out
just to keep me in time.

00:16:58.540 --> 00:17:01.600
BRADY HARAN: So what is in
time with that, then?

00:17:01.600 --> 00:17:06.695
What's happening 89
times in a minute?

00:17:06.695 --> 00:17:07.667
Can you play the track for me?

00:17:07.667 --> 00:17:08.581
Play the click track.

00:17:08.581 --> 00:17:09.579
ALAN STEWART: Yeah, sure.

00:17:09.579 --> 00:17:13.044
[CLICK TRACK PLAYING]

00:17:13.044 --> 00:17:13.833
ALAN STEWART: There you go.

00:17:13.833 --> 00:17:15.740
That's what 89 beats per
minute sounds like.

00:17:15.740 --> 00:17:18.735
And I just make sure that I kept
in time with that as I

00:17:18.735 --> 00:17:19.200
was playing.

00:17:19.200 --> 00:17:20.050
So I was going--

00:17:20.050 --> 00:17:21.300
[MUSIC AND CLICK
TRACK PLAYING]

00:17:33.307 --> 00:17:36.370
ALAN STEWART: Of course, I took
the click track out after

00:17:36.370 --> 00:17:38.600
I'd finished recording, because
no one wants to heat a

00:17:38.600 --> 00:17:39.636
click track.

00:17:39.636 --> 00:17:40.974
[CLICK TRACK PLAYING]

00:17:40.974 --> 00:17:46.330
BRADY HARAN: But Alan, I don't
really know what--

00:17:46.330 --> 00:17:49.430
because some notes you do are
short, and some are long.

00:17:49.430 --> 00:17:50.730
They don't all hit.

00:17:50.730 --> 00:17:54.153
What is the thing that's keeping
in time with that

00:17:54.153 --> 00:17:55.760
click track?

00:17:55.760 --> 00:17:58.576
Does every fourth note have
to hit the boot pedal?

00:17:58.576 --> 00:18:00.680
I don't know what you mean by
keeping in time with that.

00:18:00.680 --> 00:18:02.110
ALAN STEWART: Oh, dear.

00:18:08.320 --> 00:18:10.720
That's such a difficult
question.

00:18:10.720 --> 00:18:11.030
OK.

00:18:11.030 --> 00:18:11.453
BRADY HARAN: Play it.

00:18:11.453 --> 00:18:12.300
And talk to me of what
you're thinking

00:18:12.300 --> 00:18:14.400
and what you're doing.

00:18:14.400 --> 00:18:16.330
ALAN STEWART: You ask
a lot, Brady.

00:18:16.330 --> 00:18:18.550
BRADY HARAN: This is how these
videos get made, right?

00:18:18.550 --> 00:18:19.800
ALAN STEWART: Right.

00:18:21.990 --> 00:18:28.076
So I suppose I could play it
so that every note lands on

00:18:28.076 --> 00:18:28.980
one of the clicks.

00:18:28.980 --> 00:18:31.638
So I could play.

00:18:31.638 --> 00:18:36.598
[NOTES PLAYING]

00:18:36.598 --> 00:18:39.210
ALAN STEWART: Except the click
track just stopped, because it

00:18:39.210 --> 00:18:40.980
was only 32 bars.

00:18:40.980 --> 00:18:41.530
BRADY HARAN: Start again.

00:18:41.530 --> 00:18:42.620
ALAN STEWART: I'll
start again.

00:18:42.620 --> 00:18:43.500
I'll just loop it.

00:18:43.500 --> 00:18:45.492
BRADY HARAN: Yeah.

00:18:45.492 --> 00:18:46.330
ALAN STEWART: There we go.

00:18:46.330 --> 00:18:47.250
It's on loop.

00:18:47.250 --> 00:18:47.640
[CLICK TRACK PLAYING]

00:18:47.640 --> 00:18:49.550
BRADY HARAN: But you don't do
that, because that sound

00:18:49.550 --> 00:18:50.940
boring, is that right?

00:18:50.940 --> 00:18:52.275
ALAN STEWART: Yeah.

00:18:52.275 --> 00:18:54.890
BRADY HARAN: Then what
do you do instead?

00:18:54.890 --> 00:18:57.032
If you're going to break the
rules and not follow the click

00:18:57.032 --> 00:19:00.194
track, what's the point
of the click track?

00:19:00.194 --> 00:19:03.460
ALAN STEWART: Well, maybe if I
talk about breaking the rules,

00:19:03.460 --> 00:19:07.340
when I break the rules, I'm
taking the time interval

00:19:07.340 --> 00:19:09.840
between one click and
the next click.

00:19:09.840 --> 00:19:13.060
And I'm cutting it in
half, for example.

00:19:13.060 --> 00:19:19.150
So when one click happens, I
might play two notes of the

00:19:19.150 --> 00:19:20.130
same length.

00:19:20.130 --> 00:19:21.910
So I'll just try and
demonstrate that.

00:19:21.910 --> 00:19:24.538
[MUSIC AND CLICK
TRACK PLAYING]

00:19:24.538 --> 00:19:25.110
ALAN STEWART: No.

00:19:25.110 --> 00:19:26.870
That was notes on the click.

00:19:26.870 --> 00:19:29.690
Let me try and demonstrate.

00:19:29.690 --> 00:19:30.740
This is quite difficult.

00:19:30.740 --> 00:19:32.580
[NOTES PLAYING]

00:19:32.580 --> 00:19:33.500
ALAN STEWART: There.

00:19:33.500 --> 00:19:38.080
That's what it would sound like
to have half the click

00:19:38.080 --> 00:19:41.460
separation as a note.

00:19:41.460 --> 00:19:43.630
And I think that's how
all music and all

00:19:43.630 --> 00:19:44.910
rhythm is made up.

00:19:44.910 --> 00:19:47.320
You take the click track.

00:19:47.320 --> 00:19:50.260
And then the space in between
the clicks, you cut

00:19:50.260 --> 00:19:52.390
it perhaps in half.

00:19:52.390 --> 00:19:55.410
Or you cut it into three
pieces or cut

00:19:55.410 --> 00:19:56.860
it into four pieces.

00:19:56.860 --> 00:20:03.430
And usually you stick to notes
of those durations, so half a

00:20:03.430 --> 00:20:05.235
click or a third of a click.

00:20:05.235 --> 00:20:12.510
BRADY HARAN: But, Alan, if you
put two notes between clicks,

00:20:12.510 --> 00:20:15.610
aren't you playing at 178
beats per minute?

00:20:18.125 --> 00:20:24.830
ALAN STEWART: I suppose you
could say that I was, except

00:20:24.830 --> 00:20:31.010
that not every note is two
notes between the clicks.

00:20:31.010 --> 00:20:34.850
Some of the notes are just
the duration between one

00:20:34.850 --> 00:20:37.156
click and the next.

00:20:37.156 --> 00:20:40.150
BRADY HARAN: Do you
ever skip a beat?

00:20:40.150 --> 00:20:44.750
ALAN STEWART: Oh,
yeah, sometimes.

00:20:44.750 --> 00:20:48.380
Everything I do in this song
is some multiple of that or

00:20:48.380 --> 00:20:50.616
some division of that.

00:20:50.616 --> 00:20:53.015
I guess that's what rhythm is.

00:20:53.015 --> 00:20:53.550
BRADY HARAN: All right.

00:20:53.550 --> 00:20:56.570
Let's turn that off then,
that little click.

00:20:56.570 --> 00:20:59.410
So now we know that
89, a Fibonacci

00:20:59.410 --> 00:21:00.615
number, plays a big role.

00:21:00.615 --> 00:21:03.130
What else you got in there?

00:21:03.130 --> 00:21:05.320
ALAN STEWART: Drums.

00:21:05.320 --> 00:21:10.754
I really just need to change the
drum kit on the keyboard,

00:21:10.754 --> 00:21:17.630
which I know to be number
