I think it's punctuated.

00:22:43.140 --> 00:22:45.220
It stands out.

00:22:45.220 --> 00:22:48.540
And of course, there's also
the snare drumming.

00:22:48.540 --> 00:22:52.350
I could have done some clever
Fibonaccis with the snares.

00:22:52.350 --> 00:22:57.060
But instead, I wanted it to
remain musical sounding.

00:22:57.060 --> 00:23:00.290
Because I think if I'd based all
of the drum rhythms on the

00:23:00.290 --> 00:23:02.515
Fibonacci sequence, it would
stop sounding musical.

00:23:02.515 --> 00:23:06.470
So for that snare drums,
I just did some

00:23:06.470 --> 00:23:07.070
typical snare drumming.

00:23:07.070 --> 00:23:07.843
BRADY HARAN: Do it again.

00:23:07.843 --> 00:23:07.954
Do it again.

00:23:07.954 --> 00:23:12.325
[NOTES PLAYING]

00:23:12.325 --> 00:23:13.750
BRADY HARAN: So there's
no Fibonacci there?

00:23:13.750 --> 00:23:14.738
ALAN STEWART: No.

00:23:14.738 --> 00:23:23.630
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:23:23.630 --> 00:23:27.630
ALAN STEWART: There's one more
thing, one more element.

00:23:27.630 --> 00:23:32.900
In the chorus, if you will,
we hear this melody.

00:23:32.900 --> 00:23:38.070
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:23:38.070 --> 00:23:39.490
ALAN STEWART: Very short.

00:23:39.490 --> 00:23:45.630
That is the same melody as
Philip Moriarty and Dave Brown

00:23:45.630 --> 00:23:47.890
used in the phi song.

00:23:47.890 --> 00:23:50.980
[MUSIC - "GOLDEN RATIO SONG"]

00:23:50.980 --> 00:23:55.980
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:23:55.980 --> 00:23:58.785
ALAN STEWART: Now what does phi
have to do with Fibonacci

00:23:58.785 --> 00:24:01.545
numbers, Brady may ask.

00:24:01.545 --> 00:24:03.229
BRADY HARAN: What does
phi have to do with

00:24:03.229 --> 00:24:06.510
the Fibonacci numbers?

00:24:06.510 --> 00:24:10.770
ALAN STEWART: If you take two
consecutive Fibonacci numbers

00:24:10.770 --> 00:24:15.070
and you do the bigger one
divided by the little one,

00:24:15.070 --> 00:24:19.910
then the result is close
to the golden

00:24:19.910 --> 00:24:22.270
ratio, close to phi.

00:24:22.270 --> 00:24:25.720
Now obviously, if you choose
little Fibonacci numbers, like

00:24:25.720 --> 00:24:31.310
8 and 5, that comes
out to be--

00:24:31.310 --> 00:24:32.560
panic--

00:24:32.560 --> 00:24:33.520
8/5.

00:24:33.520 --> 00:24:34.400
What's that?

00:24:34.400 --> 00:24:38.540
1.4, which is not very close.

00:24:38.540 --> 00:24:43.230
But if you use larger Fibonacci
numbers, it tends

00:24:43.230 --> 00:24:45.960
towards the golden ratio.

00:24:45.960 --> 00:24:48.990
It gets closer and closer and
closer to the golden ratio.

00:24:48.990 --> 00:24:49.875
Proportion is divine.

00:24:49.875 --> 00:24:59.152
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:24:59.152 --> 00:25:47.555
[MUSIC - "GOLDEN RATIO SONG"]

00:25:47.555 --> 00:25:48.380
ALAN STEWART: Very nice.

00:25:48.380 --> 00:25:49.300
The proportion is divine.

00:25:49.300 --> 00:25:51.940
BRADY HARAN: You have this
mathematical, sciency

00:25:51.940 --> 00:25:52.630
background--

00:25:52.630 --> 00:25:53.820
and not even a background.

00:25:53.820 --> 00:25:56.030
You're a physics teacher.

00:25:56.030 --> 00:25:57.610
And you have this interest
in music.

00:25:57.610 --> 00:26:01.390
To what extent is music this
arty experience for you?

00:26:01.390 --> 00:26:03.720
And to what extent are you
thinking very much about

00:26:03.720 --> 00:26:07.740
numbers and octaves and science
and dividing beats

00:26:07.740 --> 00:26:10.106
into factors and things?

00:26:10.106 --> 00:26:12.480
ALAN STEWART: I think that's
a really good question.

00:26:12.480 --> 00:26:16.770
And I would say none at all.

00:26:16.770 --> 00:26:19.725
I don't think in terms
of mathematics.

00:26:19.725 --> 00:26:22.990
I don't think in terms
of the science of it.

00:26:22.990 --> 00:26:26.520
I just literally play what
I think sounds good.

00:26:26.520 --> 00:26:31.240
However, if I want to compose
a piece which is based on,

00:26:31.240 --> 00:26:36.930
say, the Fibonacci sequence or
pi, then I can use maths to

00:26:36.930 --> 00:26:41.740
map it onto music and art.

00:26:41.740 --> 00:26:44.600
And so I feel like there
is a crossover.

00:26:44.600 --> 00:26:48.865
But I'm not conscious of
it when I'm playing.

00:26:48.865 --> 00:26:51.680
BRADY HARAN: So when I drop
you an email and say,

00:26:51.680 --> 00:26:52.420
can you help me?

00:26:52.420 --> 00:26:54.690
Can you come up with some
music based on this

00:26:54.690 --> 00:26:57.590
mathematical principle, how
much is that putting a

00:26:57.590 --> 00:26:58.940
straitjacket on you?

00:26:58.940 --> 00:27:02.310
And how much is that making
it more fun and enjoyable?

00:27:02.310 --> 00:27:04.850
ALAN STEWART: I think
sometimes having a

00:27:04.850 --> 00:27:09.860
straitjacket, having a very
specific brief can actually

00:27:09.860 --> 00:27:11.140
really help.

00:27:11.140 --> 00:27:16.330
Because if you're just told to
compose some background music

00:27:16.330 --> 00:27:20.360
for, I don't know,
an elephant--

00:27:20.360 --> 00:27:20.850
actually, no.

00:27:20.850 --> 00:27:23.740
That's probably quite easy
to do, actually.

00:27:23.740 --> 00:27:30.240
But if you were just asked to
compose a nice piece of music,

00:27:30.240 --> 00:27:31.800
where do you start?

00:27:31.800 --> 00:27:34.480
Whereas if you're asked to
compose a piece of music

00:27:34.480 --> 00:27:39.040
that's based on Fibonacci, then
that does actually help

00:27:39.040 --> 00:27:41.085
to have the restriction.

00:27:41.085 --> 00:27:44.510
BRADY HARAN: Well, speaking of
restrictions, another request

00:27:44.510 --> 00:27:48.380
that I put in to you was to help
with some music for our

00:27:48.380 --> 00:27:53.790
video about calculating pi
with pies, which was an

00:27:53.790 --> 00:27:55.730
