BRADY HARAN: Obviously
you're exaggerating.

00:32:45.762 --> 00:32:46.360
ALAN STEWART: Sorry.

00:32:46.360 --> 00:32:46.780
BRADY HARAN: It's
not outrageous.

00:32:46.780 --> 00:32:48.100
ALAN STEWART: No, sorry.

00:32:48.100 --> 00:32:49.890
BRADY HARAN: Why is that
outside the box?

00:32:49.890 --> 00:32:51.410
Or why is that a twist?

00:32:51.410 --> 00:32:51.790
ALAN STEWART: Sure.

00:32:51.790 --> 00:32:54.300
Well, there have been quite
a few people who

00:32:54.300 --> 00:32:57.851
have put pi to music--

00:32:57.851 --> 00:33:03.140
Vi Hart, for one, and
some other people.

00:33:03.140 --> 00:33:06.670
And there's a very well-known
video called "The Sounds of

00:33:06.670 --> 00:33:08.940
Pi," I think.

00:33:08.940 --> 00:33:13.070
In all of the videos I've ever
seen, they've always put pi on

00:33:13.070 --> 00:33:14.340
a major scale.

00:33:14.340 --> 00:33:18.080
Professor Moriarty put pi on a
major scale on the guitar.

00:33:18.080 --> 00:33:18.390
[ROCK MUSIC PLAYING]

00:33:18.390 --> 00:33:25.230
PHILIP MORIARTY: 3, 1, 4, 1, 5,
9, bend up to 9, back to 2.

00:33:25.230 --> 00:33:35.778
And then we've got
6, 5, 3, 5, 8, 9.

00:33:35.778 --> 00:33:38.360
ALAN STEWART: So I thought I'd
like to hear what it sounds

00:33:38.360 --> 00:33:43.600
like on a minor scale,
just to see.

00:33:43.600 --> 00:33:44.880
And it sounds quite different.

00:33:44.880 --> 00:33:45.812
BRADY HARAN: Go on.

00:33:45.812 --> 00:33:48.200
ALAN STEWART: I need
to play it.

