What I did was pi times
100 divided by 3.

00:35:54.590 --> 00:35:56.772
BRADY HARAN: What else
was marching?

00:35:56.772 --> 00:35:57.015
There were drums and things,
weren't there?

00:35:57.015 --> 00:35:59.960
ALAN STEWART: In the "Pi March,"
yes, yes, the same

00:35:59.960 --> 00:36:03.640
drum beats that were in the
Fibonacci, the same

00:36:03.640 --> 00:36:04.390
principles.

00:36:04.390 --> 00:36:07.040
So the first digit of pi is 3.

00:36:07.040 --> 00:36:11.290
So there were 3 blasts on drum,
and then one blast on

00:36:11.290 --> 00:36:13.910
the drum, and then 4.

00:36:13.910 --> 00:36:16.030
And I think that stands out.

00:36:16.030 --> 00:36:16.820
That's quite obvious.

00:36:16.820 --> 00:36:26.630
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:36:26.630 --> 00:36:29.190
MATT PARKER: This is a mild
problem, because I want to go

00:36:29.190 --> 00:36:30.250
from the very edge
of the circle.

00:36:30.250 --> 00:36:32.420
But as you can see, I've
positioned all the pies.

00:36:32.420 --> 00:36:37.400
BRADY HARAN: What's it like for
you when you make a bit of

00:36:37.400 --> 00:36:40.100
music like you do for people
like me, and then you see the

00:36:40.100 --> 00:36:42.970
video on YouTube with
your music on it?

00:36:42.970 --> 00:36:45.240
What's that like?

00:36:45.240 --> 00:36:46.420
ALAN STEWART: I love it.

00:36:46.420 --> 00:36:49.700
I'm always really excited if
it's going to be a video with

00:36:49.700 --> 00:36:50.430
some music.

00:36:50.430 --> 00:36:53.492
And I guess--

00:36:53.492 --> 00:36:54.445
I don't know.

00:36:54.445 --> 00:36:56.285
It makes it come alive.

00:36:56.285 --> 00:36:57.485
BRADY HARAN: Is it
different for you

00:36:57.485 --> 00:36:58.310
when you see the video?

00:36:58.310 --> 00:37:00.870
I say, this is what the
video is about.

00:37:00.870 --> 00:37:02.927
Do you feel like, no, that's not
what I expected the video

00:37:02.927 --> 00:37:06.392
to be like, or how I expected
my music to used?

00:37:06.392 --> 00:37:11.750
ALAN STEWART: I think usually
your editing fits really well

00:37:11.750 --> 00:37:12.700
with the music.

00:37:12.700 --> 00:37:17.900
So in the pi video, you cut
on the beat, for example.

00:37:17.900 --> 00:37:21.020
Or you would cut at the
end of a phrase.

00:37:21.020 --> 00:37:24.420
And so I was really delighted
with how it looked in the end.

00:37:24.420 --> 00:37:26.150
It matched the music.

00:37:26.150 --> 00:37:34.497
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:37:34.497 --> 00:37:38.820
BRADY HARAN: Do you
like it still?

00:37:38.820 --> 00:37:40.826
ALAN STEWART: It's all right.

00:37:40.826 --> 00:37:42.740
It's got a nice bounce to it.

00:37:45.500 --> 00:37:46.590
I don't know what else to say.

00:37:46.590 --> 00:37:49.450
BRADY HARAN: You don't like
listening to you own music?

00:37:49.450 --> 00:37:52.660
ALAN STEWART: I guess
I play it.

00:37:52.660 --> 00:37:53.085
I play it.

00:37:53.085 --> 00:37:53.160
I play it.

00:37:53.160 --> 00:37:53.415
I play it.

00:37:53.415 --> 00:37:54.440
I practice it.

00:37:54.440 --> 00:37:55.170
I record it.

00:37:55.170 --> 00:37:56.120
I listen to it.

00:37:56.120 --> 00:38:01.930
And so after you've heard it
like 50 times, it loses its

00:38:01.930 --> 00:38:04.760
initial excitement and
the feeling that

00:38:04.760 --> 00:38:05.680
you get from there.

00:38:05.680 --> 00:38:08.250
And it just becomes a
song you've heard

00:38:08.250 --> 00:38:11.210
too much on the radio.

00:38:11.210 --> 00:38:16.890
But to begin with, when I first
came up with that, I

00:38:16.890 --> 00:38:20.330
just, I don't know, smiling
to myself, it

00:38:20.330 --> 00:38:21.580
just sounded so good.

00:38:24.330 --> 00:38:25.950
I like making something up.

00:38:25.950 --> 00:38:29.195
And I enjoy it for the
first hour or so.

00:38:29.195 --> 00:38:30.750
BRADY HARAN: I've made a little
list here of some of

00:38:30.750 --> 00:38:34.293
the other bits of music that I
particularly enjoy, because I

00:38:34.293 --> 00:38:36.450
just wanted to ask you a bit
about the making of them.

00:38:36.450 --> 00:38:37.160
ALAN STEWART: Yeah.

00:38:37.160 --> 00:38:39.510
BRADY HARAN: Our "Good
Will Hunting" video.

00:38:39.510 --> 00:38:42.150
Because we made a video about
mathematics in "Good Will

00:38:42.150 --> 00:38:45.510
Hunting." I emailed and said
basically, can you make

00:38:45.510 --> 00:38:47.682
something that sounds like the
theme music from "Good Will

00:38:47.682 --> 00:38:51.400
Hunting?" Because I can't
use the actual music.

00:38:51.400 --> 00:38:53.486
And you came up with this.

00:38:53.486 --> 00:38:57.680
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:38:57.680 --> 00:38:59.520
BRADY HARAN: Which
I really liked.

00:38:59.520 --> 00:39:02.390
It really sounds like the theme
of "Good Will Hunting,"

00:39:02.390 --> 00:39:06.150
without being it.

00:39:06.150 --> 00:39:07.620
Tell us about how you
came up with that,

00:39:07.620 --> 00:39:08.560
because I'm really curious.

00:39:08.560 --> 00:39:09.460
ALAN STEWART: Yeah.

00:39:09.460 --> 00:39:12.340
So I mean I've seen "Good Will
Hunting." But I can't say I

00:39:12.340 --> 00:39:13.690
remembered the music.

00:39:13.690 --> 00:39:14.380
So I went on YouTube.

00:39:14.380 --> 00:39:16.470
And I just searched for
the theme tune.

00:39:16.470 --> 00:39:21.080
And I listened to it probably
for about an hour just in the

00:39:21.080 --> 00:39:22.580
background, just having
it there.

00:39:22.580 --> 00:39:25.850
I felt like I was trying
to soak it up.

00:39:25.850 --> 00:39:30.090
And there were certain parts of
it-- because it's quite a

00:39:30.090 --> 00:39:32.030
complicated piece of music.

00:39:32.030 --> 00:39:33.380
There's loads going on.

00:39:33.380 --> 00:39:35.365
And it's a bit crazy.

00:39:35.365 --> 00:39:39.000
But there were parts of it that
I thought I can emulate

00:39:39.000 --> 00:39:42.770
what Danny Elfman, the composer,
has done here.

00:39:42.770 --> 00:39:46.240
So there's the high-pitched,
piccolo-like

00:39:46.240 --> 00:39:47.640
sound at the beginning.

00:39:47.640 --> 00:39:49.650
And then there's also something
quite beautiful

00:39:49.650 --> 00:39:53.580
about it, but also something
slightly discordant.

00:39:53.580 --> 00:39:57.890
Like in the introduction, those
piano chords are not

00:39:57.890 --> 00:40:00.650
what I would think of
as normal chords.

00:40:00.650 --> 00:40:02.780
They're a bit dissonant.

00:40:02.780 --> 00:40:03.990
They're a bit odd.

00:40:03.990 --> 00:40:09.920
So taking all those different
bits that I soaked up from it,

00:40:09.920 --> 00:40:11.040
I just tried to write something

00:40:11.040 --> 00:40:11.930
that sounded similar.

00:40:11.930 --> 00:40:25.651
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:40:25.651 --> 00:40:27.720
BRADY HARAN: When you listen
to something for a hour,

00:40:27.720 --> 00:40:32.330
though, like when a song gets
stuck in your head, how do you

00:40:32.330 --> 00:40:34.370
stop that being so stuck in
your head that you can be

00:40:34.370 --> 00:40:35.120
original with it?

00:40:35.120 --> 00:40:37.810
ALAN STEWART: I think the "Good
Will Hunting" theme tune

00:40:37.810 --> 00:40:41.485
is quite unique in that, even
after listening to it for an

00:40:41.485 --> 00:40:45.130
hour, I still find it quite
unpredictable, because it is

00:40:45.130 --> 00:40:47.670
such an interesting, rich
piece of music.

00:40:47.670 --> 00:40:49.230
There's so much going
on in it.

00:40:52.910 --> 00:40:55.570
Actually, that's why I had to
listen to it for so long.

00:40:55.570 --> 00:40:59.690
Because normally if I hear a
song four or five times, I can

00:40:59.690 --> 00:41:03.120
usually just play
it after that.

00:41:03.120 --> 00:41:06.450
But yeah, that theme tune
is complicated.

00:41:06.450 --> 00:41:08.320
So I didn't get tired of it.

00:41:08.320 --> 00:41:14.020
BRADY HARAN: Is your mimic, is
your homage to it equally

00:41:14.020 --> 00:41:14.940
unpredictable?

00:41:14.940 --> 00:41:15.870
ALAN STEWART: No.

00:41:15.870 --> 00:41:20.750
My homage to it is simple
by comparison.

00:41:24.470 --> 00:41:27.130
I feel like mine is a little
bit more tuneful.

00:41:27.130 --> 00:41:28.830
There's an actual tune that
you could sing along to.

00:41:28.830 --> 00:41:32.990
Whereas in Danny Elfman's score,
it's quite a random

00:41:32.990 --> 00:41:34.405
piece of music.

00:41:34.405 --> 00:41:38.550
And I challenge anyone to sing
the theme tune to "Good Will

00:41:38.550 --> 00:41:41.210
Hunting." Whereas, I think
mine, you could

00:41:41.210 --> 00:41:42.270
actually sing it back.

00:41:42.270 --> 00:41:42.713
BRADY HARAN: All right.

00:41:42.713 --> 00:41:45.870
Well, if anyone sings the
theme tune to "Good Will

00:41:45.870 --> 00:41:48.352
Hunting," or if they sings
Alan's version of it and post

00:41:48.352 --> 00:41:51.460
it as a video response, I will
allow the video response.

00:41:51.460 --> 00:41:52.040
ALAN STEWART: That'll
be great.

00:41:52.040 --> 00:41:53.450
BRADY HARAN: Because that
would be quite a sight.

00:41:53.450 --> 00:41:54.210
ALAN STEWART: It would.

00:41:54.210 --> 00:41:55.220
It's such a weird piece.

00:41:55.220 --> 00:42:05.445
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:42:05.445 --> 00:42:07.390
BRADY HARAN: Well, another
piece of music, this is

00:42:07.390 --> 00:42:10.210
actually more of a project
that you did quite

00:42:10.210 --> 00:42:13.250
independently of what
I was doing.

00:42:13.250 --> 00:42:15.365
And that's the "Dragon
Curve" music.

00:42:15.365 --> 00:42:16.410
ALAN STEWART: Oh, yeah.

00:42:16.410 --> 00:42:19.390
BRADY HARAN: Obviously, we did
a video about the "Dragon

00:42:19.390 --> 00:42:22.260
Curve." And there are
other animations

00:42:22.260 --> 00:42:22.870
that have been done.

00:42:22.870 --> 00:42:25.850
And you contacted the animator
and you made your own piece of

00:42:25.850 --> 00:42:26.990
music to that animation.

00:42:26.990 --> 00:42:27.590
ALAN STEWART: Hmm.

00:42:27.590 --> 00:42:28.900
BRADY HARAN: And then we sort
of brought it all together

00:42:28.900 --> 00:42:30.040
into a Numberphile video.

00:42:30.040 --> 00:42:31.035
ALAN STEWART: Yeah.

00:42:31.035 --> 00:42:33.630
BRADY HARAN: That's obviously a
really nice piece of music.

00:42:33.630 --> 00:42:35.380
Is that mathematical
or inspired?

00:42:35.380 --> 00:42:39.135
Or was that just you making
a nice piece of music?

00:42:39.135 --> 00:42:43.140
ALAN STEWART: I'd say that the
mathematical link is even

00:42:43.140 --> 00:42:46.510
weaker than the pi song,
Fibonacci song.

00:42:46.510 --> 00:42:51.410
But to me, it does reflect
things about the curve, about

00:42:51.410 --> 00:42:55.230
the shape, the way it unfolds.

00:42:55.230 --> 00:43:00.030
There are parts of it that, to
me, do connect with the shape.

00:43:00.030 --> 00:43:13.476
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:43:13.476 --> 00:43:15.070
ALAN STEWART: It's quite
difficult to explain.

00:43:15.070 --> 00:43:18.140
But one thing, actually,
about the

00:43:18.140 --> 00:43:20.770
animation is that it rotates.

00:43:20.770 --> 00:43:22.840
And so in my head, I had
the idea of circles.

00:43:22.840 --> 00:43:24.990
And in music, there's
this thing called

00:43:24.990 --> 00:43:26.800
the Circle of Fifths.

00:43:26.800 --> 00:43:30.760
And I wanted to use the Circle
of Fifths somewhere in the

00:43:30.760 --> 00:43:37.150
song to reflect that rotation
of the animation.

00:43:37.150 --> 00:43:39.370
There was something about the
animation that just looked

00:43:39.370 --> 00:43:41.750
like the original one that
looked quite lonely.

00:43:41.750 --> 00:43:46.080
And it was just a fractal
forming slowly in

00:43:46.080 --> 00:43:47.970
a vast black space.

00:43:47.970 --> 00:43:50.188
So I wanted something
that sounded lonely.

00:43:50.188 --> 00:43:59.574
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:43:59.574 --> 00:44:01.060
ALAN STEWART: Shall I
carry on talking?

00:44:01.060 --> 00:44:02.790
BRADY HARAN: Nah, you
can stop now.

00:44:02.790 --> 00:44:03.120
ALAN STEWART: Yeah.

00:44:03.120 --> 00:44:05.590
BRADY HARAN: One more thing, and
this is not Numberphile.

00:44:05.590 --> 00:44:07.370
It wasn't for a Numberphile
video.

00:44:07.370 --> 00:44:08.810
It was for a Deep Sky Video.

00:44:08.810 --> 00:44:09.410
ALAN STEWART: Yeah.

00:44:09.410 --> 00:44:11.060
BRADY HARAN: And as far as I,
know there's no math or

00:44:11.060 --> 00:44:12.010
science involved.

00:44:12.010 --> 00:44:15.830
But it's actually my favorite
piece of music that you've

00:44:15.830 --> 00:44:17.275
made for me.

00:44:17.275 --> 00:44:20.060
So I wanted to ask you about
it and hear a bit about the

00:44:20.060 --> 00:44:21.810
story from your end.

00:44:21.810 --> 00:44:24.840
And that's a piece of music that
you called "Time Passes."

00:44:24.840 --> 00:44:25.460
ALAN STEWART: Oh, yes.

00:44:25.460 --> 00:44:27.930
BRADY HARAN: I'll tell
it from my end first.

00:44:27.930 --> 00:44:30.180
Basically, I was in Paris.

00:44:30.180 --> 00:44:33.430
And I went to Charles
Messier's grave.

00:44:33.430 --> 00:44:35.558
And I'm going to stop now,
because the battery is about

00:44:35.558 --> 00:44:35.780
to run out.

00:44:35.780 --> 00:44:36.970
I'm going to change the
battery in the camera.

00:44:36.970 --> 00:44:39.375
As I was saying,
I was in Paris.

00:44:39.375 --> 00:44:42.130
And I went to Charles
Messier's grave.

00:44:42.130 --> 00:44:45.010
And I wanted a piece of music to
reflect us walking through

00:44:45.010 --> 00:44:46.430
the cemetery.

00:44:46.430 --> 00:44:47.470
And I emailed to you.

00:44:47.470 --> 00:44:48.190
ALAN STEWART: Uh-huh.

00:44:48.190 --> 00:44:50.200
BRADY HARAN: Basically I just
said, I've just been walking

00:44:50.200 --> 00:44:51.440
through a cemetery.

00:44:51.440 --> 00:44:53.400
And I want a piece of music that
shows me walking through

00:44:53.400 --> 00:44:54.430
a cemetery.

00:44:54.430 --> 00:44:59.570
And really quickly, while I was
still in the hotel, you

00:44:59.570 --> 00:45:03.600
sent me a few options
from memory.

00:45:03.600 --> 00:45:05.590
And I really liked
all of them.

00:45:05.590 --> 00:45:06.720
They were all really lovely.

00:45:06.720 --> 00:45:07.940
I could have used any of them.

00:45:07.940 --> 00:45:09.696
But in the end, I
used this one.

00:45:09.696 --> 00:45:20.720
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:45:20.720 --> 00:45:23.684
BRADY HARAN: I thought
I read about it.

00:45:23.684 --> 00:45:27.636
Straight ahead to the right of
the monument, and then right.

00:45:27.636 --> 00:45:28.886
[MUSIC - ALAN STEWART,
"TIMES PASSES"]

00:45:34.058 --> 00:45:36.480
BRADY HARAN: What happened when
I sent you this email to

00:45:36.480 --> 00:45:37.845
result in these pieces
of music?

00:45:37.845 --> 00:45:40.990
ALAN STEWART: I think I find
it easier to write

00:45:40.990 --> 00:45:42.870
sad-sounding music.

00:45:42.870 --> 00:45:44.460
So you said you were
in a cemetery.

00:45:44.460 --> 00:45:47.115
So I thought, it's
got to sound sad.

00:45:47.115 --> 00:45:49.980
You also said that the video
was going to feature you

00:45:49.980 --> 00:45:51.470
traveling to the place.

00:45:51.470 --> 00:45:54.620
So I wanted something that had a
bit of movement to it, a bit

00:45:54.620 --> 00:45:59.150
of motion, which is why it's
got a fairly fast pulse.

00:45:59.150 --> 00:46:01.440
It's like a ticking
of a clock.

00:46:01.440 --> 00:46:05.080
And that's why I called it
"Time Passes" as well.

00:46:05.080 --> 00:46:06.700
BRADY HARAN: Well, I liked it.

00:46:06.700 --> 00:46:07.165
ALAN STEWART: Thank you.

00:46:07.165 --> 00:46:07.570
BRADY HARAN: Well done.

00:46:07.570 --> 00:46:08.050
ALAN STEWART: Thanks.

00:46:08.050 --> 00:46:08.790
BRADY HARAN: Well done.

00:46:08.790 --> 00:46:10.040
[MUSIC - ALAN STEWART,
"TIMES PASSES"]

00:46:26.430 --> 00:46:29.880
BRADY HARAN: Thank you for all
the bits of music you have

00:46:29.880 --> 00:46:31.230
made for the Numberphile
videos.

00:46:31.230 --> 00:46:33.990
I know from the comments under
the videos that people

00:46:33.990 --> 00:46:37.230
watching also enjoy them.

00:46:37.230 --> 00:46:40.440
And a final reminder, ALANKEY86

00:46:40.440 --> 00:46:41.590
is the YouTube channel.

00:46:41.590 --> 00:46:43.480
Go and subscribe.

00:46:43.480 --> 00:46:45.530
Let me tell you the main reason
I want you subscribe.

00:46:45.530 --> 00:46:49.140
It's because every time I link
to Alan's channel, I get an

00:46:49.140 --> 00:46:52.520
email from him where he says,
oh, five new people have

00:46:52.520 --> 00:46:53.130
subscribed.

00:46:53.130 --> 00:46:55.450
And he gets really excited and
says he knows when I put a

00:46:55.450 --> 00:46:58.270
video up, because he'll have 10
new subscribers or 30 new

00:46:58.270 --> 00:46:59.560
subscribers.

00:46:59.560 --> 00:47:03.940
And I feel a bit disappointed
that so few people subscribe

00:47:03.940 --> 00:47:05.200
after all the hard
work you put in.

00:47:05.200 --> 00:47:08.185
So if a whole bunch of you go
and subscribe, well, that

00:47:08.185 --> 00:47:09.220
would be good, wouldn't it?

00:47:09.220 --> 00:47:10.060
ALAN STEWART: Thank you.

00:47:10.060 --> 00:47:11.630
BRADY HARAN: Yeah.

00:47:11.630 --> 00:47:12.900
Why should they subscribe,
though?

00:47:12.900 --> 00:47:15.660
They shouldn't just do it
to be nice to me or you.

00:47:15.660 --> 00:47:16.830
What are they going
to get if they do?

00:47:16.830 --> 00:47:19.640
ALAN STEWART: They will
get piano music.

00:47:19.640 --> 00:47:24.050
I try and upload maybe once a
week or once a fortnight,

00:47:24.050 --> 00:47:26.960
something I've written,
some composition.

00:47:26.960 --> 00:47:31.480
Occasionally, I'll do something
a bit different,

00:47:31.480 --> 00:47:33.270
like a song.

00:47:33.270 --> 00:47:34.080
BRADY HARAN: All right.

00:47:34.080 --> 00:47:34.770
ALAN STEWART: Yeah.

00:47:34.770 --> 00:47:37.320
BRADY HARAN: And just as a
little teaser, I know, because

00:47:37.320 --> 00:47:40.320
we were talking off camera,
that Alan is working on a

00:47:40.320 --> 00:47:44.440
couple of new compositions which
hopefully might appear

00:47:44.440 --> 00:47:47.670
on Numberphile, if I can
secure the rights.

00:47:47.670 --> 00:47:51.440
And you're doing them with
Professor Phil Moriarty, who

00:47:51.440 --> 00:47:53.880
also appears in Numberphile
in Sixty Symbols.

00:47:53.880 --> 00:47:55.970
And I have had bit
of a preview.

00:47:55.970 --> 00:47:58.520
And they're pretty exciting.

00:47:58.520 --> 00:48:00.320
They're pretty quirky.

00:48:00.320 --> 00:48:00.885
